code "Length of gestation at birth (observable entity)": '412726003' from "SNOMEDCT:2016-09" display 'Length of gestation at birth (observable entity)'

parameter "Measurement Period" Interval<DateTime>

context Patient

define "SDE Ethnicity": ["Patient Characteristic Ethnicity": "Ethnicity"]

define "SDE Payer": ["Patient Characteristic Payer": "Payer"]

define "SDE Race": ["Patient Characteristic Race": "Race"]

define "SDE Sex": ["Patient Characteristic Sex": "ONC Administrative Sex"]

define "Inpatient-Encounter": ["Encounter, Performed": "Encounter Inpatient"] Encounter
        where Encounter.lengthOfStay <= 120 days
            and Encounter.relevantPeriod ends during "Measurement Period"

define "Initial-Population": "Single Live Birth Encounter Without Galactosemia or Parenteral Nutrition With Gestational Age"

define "Single-Live-Birth-Diagnosis": distinct (
    ["Diagnosis": "Single Live Birth"]
        union ["Diagnosis": "Single Live Born Newborn Born in Hospital"]

)

define "Single-Live-Birth-Encounter": distinct ((
    "Inpatient-Encounter" Encounter
        where Encounter.diagnosis in "Single Live Birth"
        or Encounter.diagnosis in "Single Live Born Newborn Born in Hospital"
        )
        union (
            "Inpatient-Encounter" Encounter
            with "Single-Live-Birth-Diagnosis" Diagnosis
                such that Diagnosis.prevalencePeriod starts during Encounter.relevantPeriod
        )
        )

define "Single-Live-Birth-Enc-WO-Galactosemia": "Single-Live-Birth-Encounter" Encounter
    without ["Diagnosis": "Galactosemia"] Diagnosis
        such that Diagnosis.prevalencePeriod starts during Encounter.relevantPeriod
    where not (Encounter.diagnosis in "Galactosemia")

define "Single-Live-Birth-Enc-WO-Galacto-Or-Par-Nutri": "Single-Live-Birth-Enc-WO-Galactosemia" Encounter
    without ["Procedure, Performed": "Parenteral Nutrition"] Procedure
        such that Procedure.relevantPeriod starts during Encounter.relevantPeriod

define "Denominator-Exclusions": "Single Live Birth Encounter Without Galactosemia or Parenteral Nutrition With Gestational Age" Encounter
    where Encounter.facilityLocation in "Neonatal Intensive Care Unit (NICU)"
        or Encounter.dischargeDisposition in "Patient Expired"
        or Encounter.dischargeDisposition in "Discharge To Acute Care Facility"

define "Breast Milk Feeding": ["Substance, Administered": "Breast Milk"] Feeding

define "Other Than Breast Milk Feeding": ["Substance, Administered": "Dietary Intake Other than Breast Milk"] Other

define "Numerator": "Single Live Birth Encounter Without Galactosemia or Parenteral Nutrition With Gestational Age" Encounter
    with "Breast Milk Feeding" Feeding 
        such that Feeding.relevantPeriod starts during Encounter.relevantPeriod
    without "Other Than Breast Milk Feeding" Other 
        such that Other.relevantPeriod starts during Encounter.relevantPeriod

define "Single Live Birth Encounter Without Galactosemia or Parenteral Nutrition With Gestational Age": "Single-Live-Birth-Enc-WO-Galacto-Or-Par-Nutri" Encounter
    with "Gestational-AgeGToE37" Gestational
        such that Gestational.authorDatetime during Encounter.relevantPeriod

define "Gestational-AgeGToE37": ["Assessment, Performed": "Length of gestation at birth (observable entity)"] Gestational
        where (Gestational.result as Quantity) >= 259 days // 37 weeks

measure_attributes.value: Exclusive breast milk feeding for the first 6 months of neonatal life has long been the expressed goal of World Health Organization (WHO), Department of Health and Human Services (DHHS), American Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) and American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG). ACOG has recently reiterated its position (ACOG, 2007). A recent Cochrane review substantiates the benefits (Kramer et al., 2002). Much evidence has now focused on the prenatal and intrapartum period as critical for the success of exclusive (or any) BF (Centers for Disease Control and Prevention [CDC], 2007; Petrova et al., 2007; Shealy et al., 2005; Taveras et al., 2004). Exclusive breast milk feeding rate during birth hospital stay has been calculated by the California Department of Public Health for the last several years using newborn genetic disease testing data. Healthy People 2010 and the CDC have also been active in promoting this goal.
measure_attributes.name: Rationale

value_obj.value: Exclusive breast milk feeding for the first 6 months of neonatal life has long been the expressed goal of World Health Organization (WHO), Department of Health and Human Services (DHHS), American Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) and American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG). ACOG has recently reiterated its position (ACOG, 2007). A recent Cochrane review substantiates the benefits (Kramer et al., 2002). Much evidence has now focused on the prenatal and intrapartum period as critical for the success of exclusive (or any) BF (Centers for Disease Control and Prevention [CDC], 2007; Petrova et al., 2007; Shealy et al., 2005; Taveras et al., 2004). Exclusive breast milk feeding rate during birth hospital stay has been calculated by the California Department of Public Health for the last several years using newborn genetic disease testing data. Healthy People 2010 and the CDC have also been active in promoting this goal.

measure_attributes.value: Exclusive breast milk feeding for the first 6 months of neonatal life can result in numerous long-term health benefits for both mother and newborn and is recommended by a number of national and international organizations. Evidence suggests that the prenatal and intrapartum period is critical for the success of exclusive (or any) breast feeding. Therefore, it is recommended that newborns are fed breast milk only from birth to discharge.

measure_attributes.value:
A discharge to a designated cancer center or children's hospital should be captured as a discharge to an acute care facility.

It is acceptable to calculate Gestational Age using the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists ReVITALize guidelines, which define Gestational Age as calculated using the best obstetrical Estimated Due Date (EDD) based on the formula:
          Gestational Age= (280-(EDD-Reference Date))/7

where Reference Date is the date on which you are trying to determine gestational age. For PC-05, Reference Date is the Birth Date. 

Note however that the calculation may yield a non-whole number and gestational age should be rounded off to the nearest completed week. For example, an infant born on the 5th day of the 36th week (35 weeks and 5/7 days) is at a gestational age of 35 weeks, not 36 weeks.
